//www.lineups.com/articles/nfl-1st-overall-picks-list-all-time/#2007-JaMarcus-Russell] (one of the biggest draft busts of all time. Team takes some blame for using #1 pick on a player that looked to be a project, but weight/work ethic issues are on Russell.)[LINKED_TEXT: 2006: Mario Williams] [URL: https://www.lineups.com/articles/nfl-1st-overall-picks-list-all-time/#2006-Mario-Williams] (had a great career, just not HOF level)[LINKED_TEXT: 2005: Alex Smith] [URL: https://www.lineups.com/articles/nfl-1st-overall-picks-list-all-time/#2005-Alex-Smith] (never became truly elite quarterback, but has had a long and successful career)[LINKED_TEXT: 2004: Eli Manning] [URL: https://www.lineups.com/articles/nfl-1st-overall-picks-list-all-time/#2004-Eli-Manning] (will make HOF even if he shouldn’t, won 2x Super Bowls)[LINKED_TEXT: 2003: Carson Palmer] [URL: https://www.lineups.com/articles/nfl-1st-overall-picks-list-all-time/#2003-Carson-Palmer] (injuries and playing for Cincinnati likely derailed HOF-level career)[LINKED_TEXT: 2002: David Carr] [URL: https://www.lineups.com/articles/nfl-1st-overall-picks-list-all-time/#2002-David-Carr] (no question that playing for expansion team with porous offensive line messed with his game/confidence)[LINKED_TEXT: 2001: Michael Vick] [URL: https://www.lineups.com/articles/nfl-1st-overall-picks-list-all-time/#2001-Michael-Vick] (off-the-field issues limited what could have been an HOF career—Vick was inconsistent, but occasionally brilliant)[LINKED_TEXT: 2000: Courtney Brown] [URL: https://www.lineups.com/articles/nfl-1st-overall-picks-list-all-time/#2000-Courtney-Brown] (injuries)[LINKED_TEXT: 1999: Tim Couch] [URL: https://www.lineups.com/articles/nfl-1st-overall-picks-list-all-time/#1999-Tim-Couch] (playing for the Browns has to explain some of his difficulties)[LINKED_TEXT: 1998: Peyton Manning] [URL: https://www.lineups.com/articles/nfl-1st-overall-picks-list-all-time/#1998-Peyton-Manning] (HOF player)[LINKED_TEXT: 1997: Orlando Pace] [URL: https://www.lineups.com/articles/nfl-1st-overall-picks-list-all-time/#1997-Orlando-Pace] (HOF player)[LINKED_TEXT: 1996: Keyshawn Johnson] [URL: https://www.lineups.com/articles/nfl-1st-overall-picks-list-all-time/#1996-Keyshawn-Johnson] (near-HOF player)[LINKED_TEXT: 1995: Ki-Jana Carter] [URL: https://www.lineups.com/articles/nfl-1st-overall-picks-list-all-time/#1995-Ki-Jana-Carter] (injuries)[LINKED_TEXT: 1994: Dan Wilkinson] [URL: https://www.lineups.com/articles/nfl-1st-overall-picks-list-all-time/#1994-Dan-Wilkinson] (tough to grade him—had a decent career, though not for #1)[LINKED_TEXT: 1993: Drew Bledsoe] [URL: https://www.lineups.com/articles/nfl-1st-overall-picks-list-all-time/#1993-Drew-Bledsoe] (near-HOF player)[LINKED_TEXT: 1992: Steve Emtman] [URL: https://www.lineups.com/articles/nfl-1st-overall-picks-list-all-time/#1992-Steve-Emtman] (the poster boy for injuries)[LINKED_TEXT: 1991: Russell Maryland] [URL: https://www.lineups.com/articles/nfl-1st-overall-picks-list-all-time/#1991-Russell-Maryland] (similar to Wilkinson—a quality starter for many years, though not #1 player output) Looking at the last 30 years, #1’s certainly haven’t been sure things, but I’d say that a slight majority have been at least good NFL players, and several have been very good. Of the players who didn’t have good careers, you see a lot of injuries. But certainly, when you talk about players—either busts or guys who didn’t reach their full potential—the coaching/management situation seems to have been at least part of the story."},{"prompt":"Hindi language meant to unite Indians or to trigger Indians?","completion":"Unite North Indians, Maharashtrians, Gujaratis, Telugus, Kannadigas only."},{"prompt":"medication always needed for ADHD no matter how good or bad your ADHD is?","completion":"ADHD treatment involves several protocols among which are medication and cognitive behavior training. While medication still remains the first choice, it is by no means the final choice, and the specific medication will almost certainly change over time. Cognitive behavior training has demonstrated very good results in the effective management of various presenting symptoms of ADHD and I strongly recommend this, as at least an adjunct to medication."},{"prompt":"want to use C++ to learn Machine Learning instead of Python or R, is it fine?","completion":"Yes you can always learn any subject with any language, but NO, it’s NOT FINE to learn machine learning with C++. Don’t do that. The fact that Python is slow is very much exaggerated. Beginners like to argue about which language is faster etc., I did the same thing as well, but you are not writing TensorFlow, you are just trying to implement a simple gradient descent by yourself, the scale of your problem is still far away from reaching the bottleneck of language runtime speed.It’s true that TensorFlow is implemented in C++, as well as many other large scale learning frameworks (e.g. caffe, vowpal wabbit, libsvm) and to best of my knowledge, all optimization routines. However, you’ll notice that most of them have a Python or Matlab wrappers. This means that even if you build everything in Python, under the hood you are still running C++ code, so there really is no performance difference.Remember that your main purpose is to learn about ML, not to practice programming. It would cost you a lot of time to understand the mathimatical concepts in ML alone, coupling that with a language that’s more difficult to deal with will slow you down a lot. And I have to warn you that debugging C++ code for ML algorithms is very difficult. Your brain cycle is much more valuable than CPU cycle, your time is much more expensive than CPU time. So my suggestion is to do one thing at a time. Most online and university courses use Matlab or Python, just pick a course and use whatever language the course uses to implement the algorithms and solve problems. Then if you are ready to focus on some problem where the speed is an important factor, you can dive into C++ and replace some Python code with C++. Edits: Thanks to all the upvotes and comments. I feel like I need to answer some of the very valid comments here, so here we go… Machine learning and data science in general is a huge interdisciplinary area, so different people might have very different opinions. R or Python is more preferred in data analytics or data mining, while C++ is fundamental in deep learning and computer vision. This question is about whether to learn machine learning, and my answer is about that only. If the question is about what language to use in building ML applications, there’s no clear winner, because applications differ vastly. If one is trying to build a robot for example, he/she is basically stuck in ROS/C++/CMake/Linux ecosystem; if the project is to predict sales trends for a company, one might even consider Tableau for convenience.We can do a lot more than using canned libraries in Matlab or Python, in fact, in both languages you can implement a linear SVM or logistic regression without using any library, which is perfect for educational purposes. ML to its core is a set of vector or matrix operations, which is a perfect fit for Matlab and Numpy. If I were to learn ML in C++, I would certainly use Eigen for faster vector operations, the resulting code would be quite similar to Matlab/Numpy code, so why not just use Matlab instead? I don’t hold a grudge on C++, in fact C++ is my native language. It’s just each language has its pros and cons, and it’s more productive to have an open mind and choose the best language for different purposes. It isn't a good idea to claim any language to be useless."},{"prompt":"w do you deliver effective communication?","completion":"Never tell them at night unless there is something that they can do and it needs to be done before morning. Let them have that nights sleep.. Going in person is best but if not possible.. call them.. Don’t drag it out.. just be direct… I’m sorry honey, I’ve got some bad news, Mary is in ICU she had a heart attack. Her kids and hubby are with her and they think you should come as soon as possible, they don’t know if she is going to make it. Or the dr thinks she is going to have a full recovery but she’ll be in hospital for a few days.. then wait to let them talk"},{"prompt":"What are the most amazing photos you have ever taken?","completion":"Garb it or Smack it?"},{"prompt":"Which is the best travel portal development company?","completion":"TRAVELLADDER is the leading [LINKED_TEXT: travel technology company globally] [URL: https://travelladder.in/index.html#contactForm] and we serve travel companies around 50 countries across four continents. Flight booking system consists on integrating GDS system or flight APIs provided by major global distribution systems and flight consolidators. One can integrate single or multiple GDS system as well as Flight API in airline reservation system to provide vast choice of flight bookings in multiple destinations. Get a Project Quote : [LINKED_TEXT: https://travelladder.in/index.html#contactForm] [URL: https://travelladder.in/index.html#contactForm] TRAVELLADDER is a [LINKED_TEXT: travel portal development Company in India] [URL: https://travelladder.in/index.html#contactForm]. We provide online flight booking system software development offers: – Latest user interface. – Easy flight book & search system. – Multi language and currency support. – Multiple GDS integration. – Secure payment integration systems. To Know More Visit us : [LINKED_TEXT: Travelladder] [URL: https://travelladder.in/] Mail us : [LINKED_TEXT: info@travelladder.in] [URL: mailto:info@travelladder.in] Call us : 7090234334 [LINKED_TEXT: Travelladder] [URL: https://travelladder.in/]"},{"prompt":"What is your review of 'Dil Bechara' (2020 movie)?","completion":"Lagaan - 3h 44 m Mohabbatein - 3h 36m Jodhaa Akhbar - 3h 34 m Kabhi Khushi Kabhi Gum - 3h 30m Swades - 3h 30m Hum Aapke Hain Kaun - 3h 26m Sholay - 3h 24m Average duration of Bollywood movies - 2h 30m Dil Bechara - 1h 41m The movie is based on the novel \`The Fault in Our Stars' by John Green. When you make a movie out of a book, you can't make it in parts such as Dil Bechara 1, Dil Bechara 2,.. Because you would like to complete a story with climax. Dil Bechara had to be released on online platform so it had to be short. Due to this film maker had to edit it to fit the duration. I have put these details before review as I don't want to be biased just because of movie duration. Movie was full of fun in the first half where Sushant wins our heart with magical acting, comedy and dance and emotions in second half that made me cry twice. I liked the love chemistry and I couldn't take out my eyes off Sushant. I noted even the small small things such as Tshirt that Sushant was wearing. I felt it was Sushant in the character of Sushant. It was fun to watch Jamsedpur and local dialect, especially the Sushant's friend's character. It was lovely and touching. Storyline was also smooth with little suspense. The Bengali family’s conversation were also entertaining. Actress has also done justice to her role and character. A film is as good as its songs are. I was lucky to feel A R Rahman's magic. Songs were beautiful and were inline with the story. The scene that took away my heart - Funeral speech preparation scene in the church. It made my eyes moist. I loved the movie and it finished before I looked at the clock."},{"prompt":"CNN reported that 1,000 US health experts have demanded that businesses not be allowed to reopen, but protestors should not be criticized for violating suggestions and increasing infection risks. Does science not matter anymore?","completion":"No. Science no longer matters. For years, the left has called the right anti-science. They've also criticized the right for doubting or being skeptical of “experts” (I quote experts because not all are). There is no greater example that science no longer matters than the letter that just came out this week. The letter’s most telling passage: Staying at home, social distancing, and public masking are effective at minimizing the spread of COVID-19. To the extent possible, we support the application of these public health best practices during demonstrations that call attention to the pervasive lethal force of white supremacy. However, as public health advocates, we do not condemn these gatherings as risky for COVID-19 transmission. We support them as vital to the national public health and to the threatened health specifically of Black people in the United States. For four months we were told not to gather, by the experts, in order to flatten the curve. When protesters were demanding to reopen their businesses, we were told these people were dangerous and that they would be responsible for prolonging and exacerbating the problem. Fair enough. Now, a few weeks later, they are dismissing those SCIENTIFIC concerns in the name of SOCIAL JUSTICE. THIS. DOESN'T. MAKE. SENSE. Either Covid-19 is a real concern that needs to be properly addressed, or it was never a real concern and it was blown out of proportion. It can't be different depending on politics. So to answer your question: no. Science no longer matters. If you are a business owner, having a birthday or just feel like it, you should feel justified to do whatever you want in large groups. Apparently, Covid is cancelled."},{"prompt":"eard lot of gurus say go deep or go inside. Where should I go? What is go inside?","completion":"Hinduism: Start with mantra japa (e.g., om namo hanumate namaha, om namo narayanaya, om namah shivaya, etc.). You must first develop chitta-shuddhi. Mantra japa will do that. The rest will take care of itself when you have done so. Until you have done so, nothing else matters. Learn how to achieve mantra siddhi by reading the puranas and pursue it with rigor and fastidiousness. Mantra should be done for billions of repetitions. It is an ongoing process. Not something you start on Friday and get a result on Saturday. It is possible, but highly improbable."},{"prompt":"What did you get for Christmas 2017?","completion":"Complete series DVD of \\"My Family\\", re-used item from CeX. Hahahaha"},{"prompt":"'s said that the Hidden Bible Code says the rapture is in 2021. Is this true?","completion":"No. There will never be a rapture because it's all based on goat-herder fairy tales."},{"prompt":"What are your late growth spurt stories?","completion":"Dec 2008 , Bhopal Status - final year of Graduation from NIT Bhopal.. was living on literally no money but I had some good friends .. really good friends ( with whom I got ragged in morning and laughed on it in the evening) and a carefree life … Mar 2010 , Gaziabad Status - Recession hit the world in 2009 and it hits me badly too.. I didn’t receive my joining letter of company in which I was selected at campus after waiting for 10 months . Life Struggle started to find a good job . First preparing for govt exams and then appearing for it became a monthly schedule. After one written exam and two interviews finally I landed in NSN , my first company … This pic was from the farewell party after the training. Jan, 2011 - Agra Status - In NSN, I wanted to work near my hometown ( Bihar). I opted for a UP west location and I landed directly in the city that is famous for the symbol of eternal love .. new job .. new learning ..new affair everything was good .. till I faced my first breakup.. hair loss started becoming apparent .. May,2012 - Patna Status - Started getting injured mentally and physically by office Politics in my company. People came to know that I was preparing for MBA and since then things started going awry for me . A serious breakup and a hectic job life took a toll on me . I went into a mild form of depression. But this wasn’t me. This pic reminded me that home is a place where you will find happiness at any point of your time.. ( i was leaving that day ). I bounced back and started preparing for CAT (entrance exam for post graduation in India) holding on the hope of getting a better ticket to leave that job. Feb , 2013 - Mumbai Status - things were hitting rock bottom . I was in abyss. I received two back to back lowest rating in my job life . Reason - office politics and saying no to stressful back to back night duties . My internal transfer were stopped without informing me.My CAT prep friend married out of frustration after getting a low percentile next year too and I attended it . I finally received few B-school calls . I landed in city of dreams for first time for an interview and with messed up mind messed up the interviews. But somehow this city called me.. July,2013 - NITIE ( B-School ) , Mumbai Status - Finally landed in a B-School worthy enough to be on my resume … and that too in Mumbai , the city with whom i fell in love at first sight ( notice my health - my belt was tucked on the last hole and still it was loose ) Mar,2014 - NITIE ( B-School ) , Mumbai Status - fast forwarding first hectic year of MBA … multiple interviews..cramming things which needed to be learned… groomed myself in photography … started working out and then this happened I started looking better.. Yup that’s me .Suited up .. sitting up with my photography brethren of my MBA college Mar,2015 - NITIE ( B-School ) , Mumbai Status - signing off from my MBA college .This was the pic taken in the evening at the iconic location of that college after the farewell party. Things were better with me . I was placed, I was done and dusted with MBA, I learnt photography decent enough, I made some really good friends, I started looking better. Life was quite on track .. fast forward.. year of eventful moments June ,2016 - Patna my brother’s marriage July ,2016 - Roadtrip to Ladakh July ,2016 - Standup comedy in office .. and many more my life was like a roller coaster ride. It made me cry but then again I kept my hope with me and it rewarded me back with a bundle of joy every time. Hope is the best thing that was ever given to this world … Cheers.. hoping for 2017 to end at a great note"},{"prompt":"Why did James VI of Scotland, being Scottish, prefer English to Scots, imposing the teaching of English?","completion":"By Scottish do you mean the Gaelic language? There isn’t a “Scottish” language, the languages in Scotland being Gaelic, Scots and English. James I/VI was a king and his interest was in a unity across his kingdom in which loyalty was clearly owed foremost to his throne and not to alternative leadership structures and adherences. Hence the Statutes of Iona [LINKED_TEXT: Statutes of Iona - Wikipedia] [URL: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statutes_of_Iona] and [LINKED_TEXT: Citizenship and the Statutes of Iona] [URL: https://www.historytoday.com/citizenship-and-statutes-iona] There is an interesting section in the following on James and his languages, [LINKED_TEXT: The Queen’s English, The King’s Speech…? There’s a lot more to monarchs than meets the ear] [URL: https://www.etymax.com/blog/the-queens-english-the-kings-speech-theres-a-lot-more-to-monarchs-than-meets-the-ear/] Complimented by the section on “Scots Gaelic” in [LINKED_TEXT: BBC - Voices - Multilingual Nation] [URL: http://www.bbc.co.uk/voices/multilingual/scots_gaelic_history.shtml] Note the use of the terms “Erse” and “Irish” in this period. James was a king for Scotland and for England (and Wales) and that was his identity and not the modern identity of the football terraces."},{"prompt":"What would happen if we could use 100% of our brain?","completion":"We do"},{"prompt":"What is your favorite guitar joke?","completion":"Q: How many guitarists does it take to change a light bulb? A: Only one. All the other guitarists watch and say: “I could do that.” (and then there is the alternative answer) Twenty. One to change the bulb and nineteen to say, \\"Not bad, but I could've done better\\". A guy walks into the doctor's office and says, \\"Doc, I haven't had a bowel movement in a week!\\" The doctor gives him a prescription for a mild laxative and tells him, \\"If it doesn't work, let me know.\\" A week later the guy is back: \\"Doc, still no movement!\\" The doctor says, \\"Hmm, guess you need something stronger,\\" and prescribes a powerful laxative. Still another week later the poor guy is back: \\"Doc, STILL nothing!\\" The doctor, worried, says, \\"We'd better get some more information about you to try to figure out what's going on. What do you do for a living?\\" \\"I'm a musician, I play the guitar.\\" The doctor looks up and says, \\"Well, that's it! Here's 10.00. Go get something to eat!\\" Q: What does a guitar player say when he gets to his gig? A: Would you like fries with that? Q: What is the difference between a guitarist and a Savings Bond? A: Eventually a Savings Bond will mature and earn money! Q: What's the first thing a guitarist says when he knocks on your door? A: \\"Pizza!\\" Q: What do you get when you cross a chicken with a guitar? A: a chicken that makes music when you pluck it! A young child told his mother \\"When I grow up I'm going to be a guitarist.\\" His mother responded \\"Well honey, you know you can't do both.\\" Q: What does Eric Clapton and a cup of coffee have in common? A: They both suck without Cream."},{"prompt":"Why are scientists more concerned about the impact of CO2 in the atmosphere than water vapor?","completion":"What damage does water vapor do in the atmosphere? It can not get above 100% RH, otherwise, it rains. CO2, on the other hand, is at its highest concentration in millennia, at least 800,000 years. It tends to help trap heat, so our climate is warming and is starting to affect our weather and ecosystems."},{"prompt":"What is your worst cinema experience?","completion":"Late seventies…Daughter was four years old and son was a toddler. We had not been to movies for months because of the kids. Our parents visited us. “Both of you go to a movie. We will baby sit the kids” they said. But we decided to go to second show (9pm to 11.30 pm show) and take our son with us. Anyhow it was his sleep time and there will be a problem for parents if he woke up after we went out. He fell asleep as soon as the two wheeler started. He continued his sleep throughout the journey. We could some how get the last two tickets. They were the corner seats in the very first row! Any how since we have come this far we decided to see the movie sitting in those seats.Our toddler was sleeping peacefully through out the advertisements and trailers. Sitting in a corner seat in the first row, the screen looked like this: “Something is better than nothing” we thought. Here I will tell you something. Our toddler used to have constipation. So whenever he completed his #2 we would feel happy. So he decided to give us that happiness just ten minutes after the actual movie started. The happiness was not for once but twice. Each of us took turns to take him out and clean him. He would usually become active after he successfully achieved his #2. But that day he decided to become ‘hyperactive’. The vast space between the first row and the screen made him super excited. He started to run from one end to the other end with all his energy. He even tried to play hide and seek with one or two people sitting in the first row. Initially we tried to run after him but soon we gave up, because nobody complained and they even started enjoying his playfulness. One old man(we were young then) sitting beside husband went into ‘sound’ sleep just after half an hour. The ‘sound’ did not bothered many because it was some what rhythmic and finely mixed with the back ground music of the movie. But I was not very happy with that ‘remix’. Toddler was too curious. He tried to wake the old man up from his slumber but terribly failed. “Shall we go home?” I whispered into husband’s ears. “No we will stay. We have to extract maximum enjoyment(??!!) from the movie” he said. I could only see half the movie, because one of my eyes was on the screen while another was on our toddler. Toddler went into sleep as soon as the scooter started when we were returning! End of my ‘Half movie’ experience!"},{"prompt":"What are the best ways to invest money?","completion":"You should find out what your niche is before investing because there are lots of markets you can invest in. Forex, commodities, cryptocurrencies, stocks, and others can be your way towards success in investing but you need to gain knowledge, formulate strategies, and do due diligence as always."},{"prompt":"What are the most underrated cities in the U.S.?","completion":"Point Reyes, CA for its spectacularly scenic [LINKED_TEXT: environs] [URL: http://www.protrails.com/gallery/131/california/san-francisco-marin-headlands-mt-tamalpais-point-reyes/point-reyes-limantour-beach-and-limantour-spit] and superb [LINKED_TEXT: cheese] [URL: https://www.pointreyescheese.com/]Portland, OR, if only for [LINKED_TEXT: Powell's Books] [URL: http://www.powells.com/?gclid=CjwKEAiA_NmkBRCe3ubC1aWAtEcSJACxkkbqJtbBiu76wWieoMOB46zHxgCK5g5biAVOfrFUoJYOhBoCs8Pw_wcB]Mojave, CA: America's first civilian [LINKED_TEXT: spaceport] [URL: http://mojaveairport.com/] and gateway to Death ValleyChimacum, WA, just for the[LINKED_TEXT: pie] [URL: http://chimacumcafe.blogspot.com/p/desert-menu.html] (then visit [LINKED_TEXT: Hurricane Ridge] [URL: http://www.nps.gov/olym/planyourvisit/visiting-hurricane-ridge.htm])Bodie, CA: One of the last genuine Wild West [LINKED_TEXT: ghost towns] [URL: http://www.bodie.com/]"},{"prompt":"w much will liposuction cost in India?","completion":"The fat loss due to [LINKED_TEXT: liposuction] [URL: https://www.restoreclinics.in/Liposuction-Cosmetic-Treatment.php] is permanent. But significant weight gain in future can result in re-accumulation of fat. So you have to make necessary life style changes. A healthy diet & exercise should be incorporated in daily routine to maintain the results over long term. Cost of any treatment such as liposuction is based on the patients medical condition and clinic which you choose in your near city or town where this treatment is going to take place."},{"prompt":"the NDA training the toughest?","completion":"According to my knowledge and inspiration for others to grow I know one thing to become the king of of the forest and hill as like tiger or lion, I am totally familiar with this that the best training ever I have seen in my life is the Defence training of NDA. JAI HIND."},{"prompt":"have 100k which I want to invest passively. How do I and/or where do I go to get started?","completion":"I need more information about your financial needs. income for example versus capital appreciation. Are you working full time. How soon will you need the money? Can you accept market volatility."},{"prompt":"Can a squirrel scratch give you rabies?","completion":"Highly highly highly unlikely there's been one confirmed case of rabies in squrriels but make sure to keep it very clean as in my experience Squrriel bit and scratches are notorious for getting infected."},{"prompt":"investing in cryptocurrency still profitable?","completion":"Investing in [LINKED_TEXT: cryptocurrency] [URL: https://www.quora.com/How-can-one-invest-in-cryptocurrency] can be a profitable venture, but it's essential to exercise caution and do your research before diving in. Here are some steps that you should consider when investing in cryptocurrencies: 1. Choose an exchange: The first step is selecting a reputable platform or exchange where you can buy and sell cryptocurrencies such as Bitcoin or Ethereum. 2. Create an account: After choosing the exchange, create an account by providing personal information like name, email address, phone number, and government-issued ID for verification purposes. 3. Set up a payment method: Connect your bank account or credit card to enable depositing funds for buying cryptocurrencies. 4. Select the Cryptocurrency of interest: Once you have deposited funds into your exchange wallet select which cryptocurrency you would like to invest by placing Buy orders at the current market price. 5. Secure Your Wallet/Exchange Account: It is very important that one secures their Cryptocurrency investment from unwanted parties. As such, make use of Two-Factor authentication processes offered on most exchanges as well maintaining strong passwords. 6. Monitor Market Trends: Keep tabs on news articles related to cryptocurrency tracking social media conversations/blogs written about the particular coin/token being invested. Remember that investing in cryptocurrency has risks just like any other investment plan available out there despite its rapid rise over recent years so ensure critical thinking before putting money down! You are guaranteed to get the best with investment. pro"},{"prompt":"What are the qualities of a successful leader?","completion":"he most important qualities of a leadership are - 1) Dedication, Commitment and Determination Dedication, commitment and determination to complete a task successfully and being always ready to face any kind of challenges is a Leadership characteristic. 2) Leadership is a Passion Leadership is a passion. Thinking out of the box, being innovative, and going against the waves is leadership. 3) Ability to Take Lead in Unforeseen Situations At times, the situation where we can show our leadership quality is known ahead and we are well planned and prepared to handle it. 4) Being Bold and Leading Good attitude, ability to learn, taking risks, being bold, taking ownership, leading people, etc. are some of the important leadership skills. 5) Hard Work If we read the autobiography of any leader, we can clearly see that almost everyone would have struggled a lot to get to that position and nobody was born with a silver spoon. 6) Finding Opportunities A true leader tries to find opportunity in everything they see and hear. They try to pave a further way from these findings and get benefit out of it. 7) Having Clear Vision A leader needs to have a clear vision, take the team along with him during rough times, stand for them, motivate them, and bring out the best from them. 8) Walking the talk How much even an individual tries to show off false leadership by pretending, it fades away with reality and one can clearly make out whether it is real or artificial. So, a leader needs to walk the talk. 9) Leader is a Mentor a leader needs to be very careful at every moment, as Being a leader, he is the focal point and hence must keep in mind that someone is watching him and trying to copy him and should always avoid doing things that are unethical. 10) Taking Ownership Leadership does not mean owning a big organization or leading a team of 200 to 2000 people. It is simply taking ownership. It is taking any task to closure from the beginning till the end, without losing focus. [LINKED_TEXT: Leadership development training] [URL: https://www.learnow.live/blog/how-to-build-a-successful-leadership-training-program] is not for everyone. Some employees are ready and willing to learn new skills while others are not. You can recognize a leader’s potential by identifying their passion and desire to inspire others."},{"prompt":"What is the best thing I can do before I die?","completion":"Give new direction and guidelines that help him to secure his life till his or her 4th generation."},{"prompt":"w do I change Amazon Prime Video subtitles and language?","completion":"Open the Amazon Prime Video app.Pick an episode or movie you want to watch.Tap the screen to bring up the controls.Tap the speech bubble icon on the top right.Pick any option available in the left column, which is titled Subtitles."},{"prompt":"There are 81 members in a Telegram group, however, there are 300+ views. How is it possible?","completion":"Because your group is public and 300+ users viewed your group, and out of 300+, 81 are your group members. In public group, anyone can see your group content and it becomes views. Please upvote my answer if helpful to you"},{"prompt":"Why are there still statues of confederate generals in the US? Weren’t they supposed to be taken down after the war?","completion":"The answer depends on the location of the statue. Only statues located on public land can be removed legally by government entities. If I had a statue of Robert E Lee in my backyard, no one including the government, could remove it without my permission. Of course it could be vandalized. Therefore statues on private land belong to the land owner and are personal property. Removal without the owner’s permission is theft. Destruction or defacement is vandalism. Both theft and vandalism are punishable by law, both statutory and civil. Public lands are also governed by public opinion, therefore statues, signs and other objects of political religious, racial, or sexually insulting, etc. are often removed - not just Confederate statues. Try to put a creche in front of the court house in some places and see the result."},{"prompt":"Why are there still statues of confederate generals in the US? Weren’t they supposed to be taken down after the war?","completion":"As opponents of the statues will eagerly inform you, most of the Confederate statues didn’t even go up until long after the war and reconstruction, when the ex-Confexerate states were politically in the control of Southern white people, who of necessity accepted being back in the Union, but were nostalgic for their “Lost Cause.” There was no legal bar by then against their putting up statues and other memorials to Confederates. Even in the North, the prevailing view by the late 19th and early 20th century was that the Confederate cause had been misguided but mostly well intentioned, and there was little objection to paying respects to Confederate heroes. In the view of the more fervent present-day opponents of these statues, the Confederate memorials and flag displays were intended not just as nostalgia, but as symbols of an ongoing fight against black civil rights. I’m not sure this is the whole story, but I suppose it’s true to some extent."},{"prompt":"What high protein Indian vegetarian food sources are available for people that go to the gym and want to bulk up while also losing fat?","completion":"1. Dal (lentils): Lentils are packed with protein, fiber, and complex carbohydrates. They are also low in fat and calories, making them an ideal bulking food for those looking to lose fat. 2. Soybeans: Soybeans are another great vegetarian source of [LINKED_TEXT: protein food] [URL: https://bloggmania.com/everything-you-need-to-know-about-protein/]. They are packed with all the essential amino acids and are low in fat and calories. 3. Nuts and seeds: Nuts and seeds are high in protein and healthy fats, making them ideal for bulking up while also losing fat. 4. Quinoa: Quinoa is a complete protein, meaning it contains all the essential amino acids. It is also high in fiber, making it a great choice for bulking up while also losing fat. 5. Paneer (Indian cheese): Paneer is made from cow’s milk and is a great source of protein. It is also low in fat and calories, making it an ideal bulking food for those looking to lose fat. 6. Chickpeas: Chickpeas are high in protein and are also a great source of complex carbohydrates, making them an ideal choice for bulking up while also losing fat. 7. Peanuts: Peanuts Please UPVOTE If Helpful."},{"prompt":"What are the differences between those who succeed slowly and those who succeed fast?","completion":"The ones that succeed fast Do. The ones that succeed slow Contemplate then Do. And then there are those do not succeed that simply don’t Do anything. By “Do” I am talking about mainly the uncomfortable, difficult, and hard tasks that others are unwilling to do. Those that succeed the fastest are those that act, fully invest into their decision to act, and then learn as much as they can from it. But they jump from experience to experience as quickly as possible, trying out things rather than contemplating about them. Those that still succeed, but at a much slower rate are those that contemplate their decisions first. They take the safer track by figuring out possible results and scenarios and then choose the best option after a while of contemplation. Then, however, they act just as seriously as the ones that succeed the fastest. The people that do not succeed at all, are those often too afraid to act despite having contemplated a lot. They talk themselves out of their decisions, do not stand behind them fully, and waste time entertaining themselves at all times instead. The big thing to note here is that the people that succeed fast, the ones jumping from experience to experience, still think about their choice, but not overly so. They will still gather the information readily available and think about the choice before making it. However, most of these choices will still be made within the hour if not within the day. For them, few choices take longer to commit to than that. Whereas the ones that succeed slowly may take weeks, months, or even years to decide, but they eventually do go through with it. The big thing that sets up those succeeding quickly from the ones that succeed slowly and those again from those that will not succeed at all is the belief in themselves they have. The ones that succeed fast belief they can handle anything. This type of primal confidence often comes with a certain amount of arrogance and pride, which is why most people at the height of their fields are deemed as narcissists or selfish people. The ones that still succeed, but slower, also believe they can handle a lot, but are not willing to test whether or not they can handle anything. They would rather avoid certain situations due to their own disbelief or the fear they have of maybe not being okay with the consequences of their choice and so they hold themselves back. And the ones that do not succeed at all are so terrified of these consequences that they do not step out at all. Which means, in the end, it is all about Self-Belief and Courage. The courage to act and to take responsibility for ones actions, and the overall belief that one can move through these things, whatever they may be, are things that not everybody possesses. But in developing those things one can become less bound, less restricted, less limiting of oneself, which is often the biggest reason for ones own shortcomings and lack of success."},{"prompt":"Social Science","completion":"It depends about what you mean by science. But if science is a knowlegde about something, which which I agree, social science is a real science."},{"prompt":"What are the disadvantages a person can have after becoming a member of a Freemason?","completion":"I know of companies where if you aren’t a Mason you don’t get promoted. I was preparing to send a resume to a manufacturer of aircraft engines and a friend happened to notice it and gave me a heads up from a friend of his who’d worked there. I threw that one in the trash and never sent it."},{"prompt":"Bangladesh more powerful and prosperous than Pakistan?","completion":"Depends on what you mean by far. Bangladesh is certainly ahead of Pakistan in Gross domestic produce (both PPP and non-PPP) and it has much better human development indicators. If the current trends continue for the next few decades and it looks like they will as Pakistan does not have its act together — than Bangladesh will certainly be far more prosperous than Pakistan."},{"prompt":"f you agree with Mitch McConnell and Paul Ryan that its time to cut Medicare, Medicaid, and Social Security because the deficit has skyrocketed, what percentage of cut to each program would you support?","completion":"Are you sure that the deficit skyrocketed ??? [LINKED_TEXT: Remarks by President Biden on Historic Deficit Reduction - The White HouseRoosevelt Room 11:34 A.M. EDT THE PRESIDENT: Good morning. I ran for President to rebuild the backbone of the middle class — this country — that’s the backbone — to build an economy from the bottom up and the middle out and for — make sure the economy was stronger than it was before the…https://www.whitehouse.gov/briefing-room/speeches-remarks/2022/10/21/remarks-by-president-biden-on-historic-deficit-reduction/] [URL: https://www.whitehouse.gov/briefing-room/speeches-remarks/2022/10/21/remarks-by-president-biden-on-historic-deficit-reduction/]I think that Mitch McConnell is a liar. Pant in Fire Liar. Since the deficit has been reduced, can we double the Medicaid/Medicare program."},{"prompt":"Why is Weedmaps asking for a medical card when ordering for delivery in California? I thought it was legal.","completion":"Marijuana is legal in California. However, there are still medical sales. The only advantage to the medical card is that you will not have to pay sales tax. You still have to pay the state tax. To get a medical card you need a prescription from a doctor. You take that to the county health department (at least in my county) and pay a fee. They issue the one year card. After a year, you renew. I concluded it wasn’t worth the time, effort, and money."},{"prompt":"What are the differences between the Gospels of Matthew, Mark, Luke and John? Which one should be read first or last? Why?","completion":"There are two publications that I suggest that you read. The Greastest Man Who Ever Lived and Jesus, The Way, The Truth, The Life. These can be found on [LINKED_TEXT: http://jw.org] [URL: http://jw.org/] and will take you thru his complete life. As each step is covered there will be references to the books of Matthew, Mark, Luke, and John so that all scriptures found therein are covered."},{"prompt":"Which Bollywood movie has a very effective, well crafted, and brilliant climax scene?","completion":"I have not much knowledge about jugding the climax scene but there are very beautiful crafted Bollywood movies are there which I share with you. Hope you like it… Zindagi na milegi dobaraKapoor & sonsYeh jawani h dewaniUdaanGuzaarish Their stories are just good but the strong direction and acting makes the movie very impactful . I consider only last 10 years movies so that you can judge that easily.Any suggestions are welcome."},{"prompt":"New theory: in Endgame, could Tony Stark have given Steve Rogers a metal shield (instead of vibranium) before the final battle since he is still a little mad at him? Could that be why Thanos broke it so easily?","completion":"No. The shield took way too many hits for that to be the case. Why did it break? Its old. The thing has suffered a lot of punishment over the years. Tends to make things a bit weaker.Vibranium is the strongest metal on earth, not the strongest metal in the universe. Thanos’ sword could easily be made of some super alien metal/alloy.Following the above, vibranium isn’t indestructible. Especially now that the MCU has adamantium back.The shield is meant to receive blows on its face, not its edge. Especially not heavy continuous blows onto one small point on the shield’s edge. Once he made a chip on the shield, it was all over. It was a fatal weakness that compromised the entire shield. Your conspiracy theory might be more interesting if something like this concept had happened."},{"prompt":"w does one get officially married if they don’t believe in God? Would you still have to have a priest?","completion":"I’ve been married 3 times. My first wife knew of my religious leanings but we got married in church because that’s what she wanted. There were religious readings in the service. Sadly, she died. My second wife wasn’t particularly religious and we got married in a registry office with no religious mentions at all, and just the registry office official overseeing the service. She fucked off after 49 weeks (and it didn’t take me long after that to realise that I’d had a lucky escape). My third (current, and last) wife is also fully aware of my religious beliefs. We got married in Central Park with just us, an officiant and a witness. We wrote our own vows and there was nothing in there (from either side) to indicate religion. Officially, I’ve been married three times. I had/have an official document that proves it."},{"prompt":"What is a list of skills that are amazing if you learn them?","completion":"There are many skills that can be beneficial to learn, and the specific skills that are most useful for you may depend on your goals and interests. Here is a list of some skills that are generally considered to be useful or valuable: Communication skills: These include verbal and written communication, as well as listening and interpersonal skills.Problem-solving skills: The ability to analyze problems and come up with effective solutions is important in many fields.Time management skills: Being able to organize your time effectively and prioritize tasks can help you be more productive.Leadership skills: These skills can help you inspire and motivate others, and are valuable in many professional settings.Adaptability: Being able to adapt to new situations and learn new things quickly can be a valuable asset in a rapidly changing world.Creativity: The ability to think outside the box and come up with new ideas can be useful in many fields.Critical thinking skills: The ability to analyze and evaluate information and arguments is important for making sound decisions.Intercultural skills: The ability to understand and work effectively with people from different cultures can be valuable in a globalized world.Computer skills: Familiarity with computers and various software programs is important in many fields.Resilience: The ability to bounce back from setbacks and failures can be important for personal and professional success. This is just a partial list, and there are many other skills that may be valuable depending on your goals and interests."},{"prompt":"What is onpage SEO?","completion":"On-page SEO, also known as on-site SEO, refers to the optimization strategies and techniques applied directly to a website's individual pages to enhance its search engine rankings and visibility. The main objective of on-page SEO is to make a webpage more relevant and understandable to search engines, which improves its chances of appearing higher in search engine results pages (SERPs) for relevant keywords or queries. It involves various factors such as keyword optimization, where relevant keywords are strategically incorporated into the page's title tag, headings, meta descriptions, URL, and content. Creating high-quality and valuable content that satisfies user intent is also crucial, including natural keyword usage, proper formatting, and user-friendly organization. Other aspects include crafting informative and compelling meta tags, creating clean and descriptive URLs, using appropriate heading tags, optimizing images, establishing internal links, focusing on user experience, and implementing structured data markup. By implementing these on-page SEO practices effectively, website owners and marketers can improve a webpage's visibility, attract organic traffic, and ultimately achieve better search engine rankings."},{"prompt":"What do I need to know about the University of Toronto?","completion":"Uoft is a different playing field compared to highschool, 100%, however that doesn’t mean you can’t have fun while stressing about studying and exams. Currently being a living breathing UofT student, Some of my suggestions are: Talk to people, say hi, thank you, excuse me, can you …” it’s going to be o lonely and depressing if you don’t talk to people, I was miserable my entire statistics class until I asked for the person beside me for help and we’re good friends now.Drop the class if you can not stand it past the second week of school. Literally, if you can not pay attention or fall asleep your wasting your money to pay a prof to help you nap, either take up coffee or take it another semester/drop it completelyFind you textbooks online. Why on earth would you drop 500 on textbooks when they exist online or second hand. This money you spend on textbooks will not add up to the amount of time you actually use it at ALL.You're most likely going to fail a test, assignment, exam, something within your first year. You can define failing, for me, that’s getting anything lower than a 50, some people have a heart attack over not getting at 80. calm down, cry for a minute, call your mom or best friend, and then LEARN from your mistakes and do better. You have no time to complain, you came here to learn, that also includes learning the new standards and expectations of a different institution.EXPLORE, HAVE FUN, ENJOY YOUR TIME. I regret stressing so much first year. My favourite memories are going to the ROM between classes, not what the prof rambled on for 2 hours, sure you'll have good interesting lessons, but the stuff you do outside of class is all you’re gonna remember at the end of the year."},{"prompt":"What is the political leaning of MSNBC's Morning Joe show?","completion":"Joe Scarborough is a traditional conservative, and was a mainstream Republican Congressman from Florida. While he was in Congress, for example, he signed the “Contract with America” and voted to impeach Bill Clinton. [LINKED_TEXT: Joe Scarborough - WikipediaAmerican cable news and talk radio host, lawyer, author, and politician (born 1963) Charles Joseph Scarborough ( / ˈ s k ɑːr b ʌr oʊ / ; born April 9, 1963) is an American television host, attorney, political commentator, and former politician who is the co-host of Morning Joe on MSNBC with his wife Mika Brzezinski . He previously hosted Scarborough Country on the same network. A former member of the Republican Party , Scarborough served in the United States House of Representatives for Florida's 1st district from 1995 to 2001. Scarborough was also a visiting fellow at the Harvard Institute of Politics at the Harvard Kennedy School of Government . [1] He was named in the 2011 Time 100 as one of the most influential people in the world. [2] Early life and education [ edit ] Scarborough was born in Atlanta in 1963, the son of Mary Joanna ( née Clark) and George Francis Scarborough, a businessman. He has two siblings. [3] In 1969, his family moved to Meridian, Mississippi , and then to Elmira, New York in 1973, and Pensacola, Florida in 1978. [3] Scarborough attended Pensacola Catholic High School in Pensacola. He earned a Bachelor of Arts degree in history from the University of Alabama in 1985 and a Juris Doctor from the University of Florida College of Law in 1990. [4] During this time, he wrote music and produced CDs with his band, Dixon Mills, including the album Calling on Robert E. Lee , [5] and he also coached football and taught high school. Legal career [ edit ] Scarborough was admitted to the Florida Bar in 1991 [4] and practiced law in Pensacola. [6] Scarborough's most high-profile case was briefly representing Michael F. Griffin , [7] [8] [9] who murdered Dr. David Gunn in 1993. He made several court appearances representing Griffin, before removing himself from the case, [10] later saying: \\"There was no way in hell I could sit in at a civil trial, let alone a capital trial,\\" referring to the prospect of prosecutors seeking the death penalty against Griffin. [11] Scarborough assisted Griffin in choosing other counsel from the many who offered their services, however, and helped shield the family from the media exposure, pro bono . [12] [13] Scarborough's political profile was also raised when he assisted with a petition drive , in late-1993, opposing a proposed sixty-five percent increase in Pensacola's property taxes. [6] U.S. House of Representatives [ edit ] Elections [ edit ] Scarborough in 1995 In 1994 , Scarborough was elected to the U.S. House of Representatives for Florida's 1st congressional district , becoming the first Republican to represent the Florida Panhandle since Reconstruction . The seat had become open when eight-term Democratic incumbent Earl Hutto retired. In the general election, Scarborough defeated the Democratic candidate, Pensacola attorney Vince \\"Vinnie\\" Whibbs Jr., with 61 percent of the vote. Whibbs was the son of former Pensacola mayor Vince Whibbs . This district had not supported a Democratic candidate fhttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joe_Scarborough] [URL: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joe_Scarborough]When he was hired by MSNBC in 2003, he toned down his conservatism a bit, but still remained largely critical of Democratic candidates, and only mildly critical of conservatives. His first book in 2005 was critical of Democrats in particular and spending programs in general, and his second book a few years later continued the trend. His third book, in 2013, was still largely a defense of Reagan Republican. Through that period and beyond, the only Republican candidate that Scarborough seemed to consistently disagree with was Donald Trump. Scarborough feels that Trump is dishonest, unstable, unqualified, prejudiced, and selfish. Scarborough feels that the Republican Party is hurting itself by continuing to support Trump. Even though much of what Scarborough said about Trump turned out to be true, Scarborough still does not believe that Trump should be prosecuted. [LINKED_TEXT: ‘Morning Joe': Scarborough Questions Merits of Indicting Trump: ‘It Will Set an Absolutely Horrendous Precedent’ (Video)The MSNBC host agrees with former attorney general Bill Barr when it comes to Trump's Mar-a-Lago ordealhttps://www.yahoo.com/video/morning-joe-scarborough-questions-merits-163634553.html] [URL: https://www.yahoo.com/video/morning-joe-scarborough-questions-merits-163634553.html]I have only watched the show a few times, and it strikes me that except for the issue of Donald Trump, Scarborough remains a conservative on most issues. He is closer to the middle of the road than he used to be, but that seems to be more in the interest of fairness than in pushing one side or the other. Scarborough seems to dislike Trump personally, but that does not seem to be a political issue. I disliked Trump back when he was a Democrat, and still dislike him now. It has little to do with where Trump stands on the issues, it has to do with Trump being a horrible person. Scarborough famously left the Republican Party when they voted for Trump, but is still mostly a conservative. I get the feeling that if Republicans go back to the issues, he will return. [LINKED_TEXT: Joe Scarborough to Bill Maher: The Republican Party Is DeadThe “Morning Joe” co-host also argued on “Real Time with Bill Maher” that Senators Ted Cruz and Josh Hawley are “seditionists” who deserve to be behind bars. https://www.thedailybeast.com/joe-scarborough-tells-bill-maher-that-the-republican-party-is-dead] [URL: https://www.thedailybeast.com/joe-scarborough-tells-bill-maher-that-the-republican-party-is-dead]"},{"prompt":"w many gun owners have actually stopped a crime from being committed by using a gun?","completion":"FBI records show that between one and five million crimes are stopped each year by law abiding gun owners. Thier records are not more accurate than that because more times than not, once the criminal has left the scene of the attempted crime, so does the gun owner and rarely do those attempts get reported. Kind of like, almost having a car wreck, you don’t report those to our insurance company. Now Home Invasion, B&E, some bodily harm happened or if a weapon is discharged, it will get reported."},{"prompt":"What are some rookie mistakes in running?","completion":"It truly depends on the runner. But let me list a few common mistakes I have seen in the past. Not understanding that running is a “long game\\" — If you really want to accomplish something with your running you have to be willing to look out months and years. My first 10 mile race I started training for seven months out, and I probably should have started earlier. I just finished my second Race 13.1 in Baltimore. I had a good run last year, I trained for the last twelve months just to have a better run this year. It takes time, discipline, and perseverance to get better at running.Getting frustrated too easily — Again, it is a long game. You may need to limit your running to 2 miles, 4 times a week, for 3 months before you can increase your time or distance. So be it. Stick with it.Refusing to acknowledge the need for rest — It is better to run less frequently, say 4 days a week and increase mileage per run, than to run more often, 6 days a week, and run fewer miles. This is especially true if you want to be running into your 60s. Let your body rest, or at least the joints you're putting into running.Cross training — On the days your don't run it is important to do other things, yoga, stretching, weights. Building muscle mass is important and running isn't the only thing you should have in your toolkit.Nutrition — I got a big fat F on this one as a young rookie. Just because you run a lot, it doesn't mean you can eat anything you wish. It really doesn't. I eat a very low carb diet, except the day before a half marathon, then I eat carbs, maybe two days before. The rest of the time I eat a lot of protein, fruits, and vegetables. No bread, pasta, pizza, white rice, etc. This is overly simplistic, but point is, nutrition.Understanding how YOUR body works — you have to figure out what works for you and where your true limits reside, then work your goals around those limits. I just finished a half Marathon. Out of 908 runners I was 60th overall, 3rd place in the 50-54 men's group of 50 or so runners. With a pace of 7:27 a mile. But, that's mediocre compared to the truly good runners. I'm going to work to be better but I know my limits and my body. Understand what you're capable of and work to achieve against that.Varying your training — vary your training. Run intervals. Do some speed work. Research some training programs. Read. Try different things. This is essential if you're going to get better over time.Shoes — Shoes are super important. You need to try different types. See what works for you. Hit a store like Road Runner. Have them check your arches and get the custom inserts. It is worth the 80 bucks. Get shoes for training and shoes for racing. And swap your shoes every 500 miles or so. Hope this is helpful. Best of luck."},{"prompt":"Was Iran/Persia powerful before? Was it full of barbarians as mentioned in the movie “300”? If it was, then did Persians raise the three empires of Achamedians, Safavid, and Sasanian?","completion":"The fact is that the Persian Empire were more efficiently managed than the Greek city states. Persians were able to maintain a multicultural empire while only a small minority in it were ethnically Persians. Soldiers of different races fought effectively under the Persian standard. As for in Greece, Sparta's conquest of Achaeans and Messenians turn themselves into \\"slaves\\" of the conquered and were forced to follow a strict and cruel code of living in order to keep the Helots from revolting. Also, subjects in the Persian empire got more freedom than the Greeks. In Greek city states, a majority of the population were slaves, outnumbering citizens 2:1, in Sparta it's 7:1. In Persia slaves were only a very small minority and there was no significant use of slaves in cultivation like the in Greece and SPQR."},{"prompt":"the Indian economy in a real crisis?","completion":"The Indian economy has had the distinction of being one of the fastest growing economies in the world over the last three decades. Yet, today there is a sense of economic malaise in the air. The young are feeling frustrated as there are too few good jobs on the horizon for them. Rural areas are in distress as farm incomes have stagnated. Corporate investment has declined. Banks burdened with bad loans are finding it difficult to lend. Exports have declined. There are telltale signs of the onset of a further slowdown. The Government is also showing signs of panic. Soon after witnessing the unease in the corporate sector after her budget speech in July 2019, the Finance Minister started holding consultations with business leaders to assuage their displeasure. The tax surcharge on income of over Rs 2 crore on capital gains of individual and institution investors (domestic and foreign) has been removed; only that on salaries and rent received by individuals remains. Several other measures have been announced: the merger of some public sector banks, recapitalisation, loan melas and moratorium on repayment of micro, small and medium enterprise (MSME) loans. All of these, except the last one, are supply side measures and are unlikely to have much of an impact anytime soon on stimulating demand. Will the corrective measures recently taken by the government arrest the slowdown? If they do not, what would? The measure that has received the most media attention is the corporate tax cut. In the third week of September came the announcement that the corporate tax rate would be cut from 30% to 22% for firms that do not seek any exemptions and from 35% to 25% for those who do. For manufacturing firms the tax rate would be as low as 15% for those making investments after October 2019. The news was welcomed by the corporate sector and boosted the Sensex index on the day of the announcement by as much as 4.5%. How did such a state of affairs come to pass in this fast growing country? Will the corrective measures recently taken by the government arrest the slowdown? If they do not, what would? This essay is an attempt to answer these questions by examining the genesis of the present problems and then asks what should be the way forward. The goal is to put together a plausible and coherent story. 1. Development in a Dual Economy Before we start putting together an explanation for the present state of affairs, we should understand the structure of the Indian economy. Let us start by defining the terms ‘formal’ and ‘informal’. The ‘formal’ sector consists of all the registered firms (i.e., firms employing 10 or more employees) plus the government sector. The ‘informal’ sector consists of the rest. Typically, formal sector jobs are better jobs in which the workers get some basic benefits like provident fund, pensions, etc. Informal sector workers do not. Agriculture -- the sector that employees the largest part of Indian labour force (over 40%) -- is informal. Much of the rural economy is informal and so is a part of the urban economy. Eighty percent of India’s population makes their living in the informal sector and produces half of India’s GDP. Almost all the poor toil in the informal sector. Consider India as a dual economy made up of two free trading regions – “Urban” and “Rural”. Urban is more developed and hence the average incomes are higher there. This is so because typically Urban growth is based on productivity growth in the formal sector while Rural growth is based much more on productivity growth in the informal sector (agriculture). Typically, labour productivity and also the potential for productivity growth tends to be higher in the formal sectors like industry than in an informal sector like small-scale agriculture. Faster industrial growth would allow agricultural labour to move to higher productivity jobs in industry, and this can be a significant contributor to the overall growth propelled by productivity growth in each sector. When there are fewer farmers left tilling the same amount of land, they too see an increase in their incomes. There can be a further increase in agricultural incomes through productivity gains in agriculture. When rural incomes rise, they also result in an increased demand for industrial goods, thus producing a virtuous cycle of growth. This is what happened in successful Asian countries. Not only did they grow fast, but they also managed to drastically reduce poverty in a generation. All developed countries have gone through this process. Even large agricultural exporting countries like the United States (US), Canada and Australia have a miniscule percentage of their labour living off agriculture now. The two oft repeated questions: ‘Why is the economy not creating enough good jobs?’ and ‘Why is there such rural distress?’ have a common answer. India has not succeeded in producing enough high productivity jobs to draw labour away from agriculture. Of course, there are further reasons for the present distress in rural areas, demonetisation being an important one. We will discuss these later. If developed countries underwent this process and so did many other Asian countries, why is India taking so long to do this? To understand this let us first understand the strategy employed by the successful Asian countries. 2. A Successful Developmental Strategy Except for the city-states like Hong Kong and Singapore, all the successful Asian countries were primarily agrarian before they industrialised. What they accomplished within 20 years was a total transformation of their economies. Initially, the policymakers concentrated on increasing productivity in agriculture. This directly increased the incomes of the rural population, and, in addition, allowed a higher level of agricultural exports that would, in turn, enable imports of machinery and technology. When a country industrialises in a transformative way, it needs to undertake some major structural reforms. Late-developing countries have the advantage that they can rapidly improve their productivity by transferring technology from developed countries rather than having to invent it themselves. Some of the technology transfer is done through foreign investment and the rest through direct purchase or copying. However, in order to absorb the transferred technology they need a well-trained labour force and supporting infrastructure. Moreover, in order to sustain a high rate of capital formation, they needed to have a high rate of domestic savings. All the Asian success stories paid due diligence to these essential aspects of development. When a country industrialises in a transformative way, it needs to undertake some major structural reforms. In order to facilitate a movement of land and labour to their more productive use, laws pertaining to land and labour may have to be reformed. In order to facilitate savings by households, the financial system needs to be modernised. The financial system should be easily accessible for people no matter where they live and also it should be able to inspire trust. Foreign investors should be assured of legal protection of their intellectual property rights. The success of these Asian countries was based on these basic preliminaries. Another crucial aspect of their development strategy was to start by focusing on producing labour-intensive goods (textiles, footwear, toys, etc.) for the markets in developed countries. They could thus take advantage of their cheap labour and then produce these goods in quantities far in excess of what they could have sold domestically. Thus, domestic demand was never a constraint for them in expanding their industries producing goods in which they had a comparative advantage. There is a certain logic behind this export-led strategy for fast growth. First, when firms can see that there is a potential market for their products they are inclined to make investments. Second, to be able to accumulate capital, a country needs to have a high savings rate; but high savings imply low domestic consumption and hence low domestic demand. However, when a country produces for foreign markets, the trade-off between savings and consumption becomes irrelevant. It can afford to have a high savings rate domestically. With access to export markets, it can have both high domestic savings and high demand coming from consumption abroad. In addition, there is a much greater choice in what to produce as the world demand is bound to be more diverse than domestic demand. The manufacturing sector, especially labour-intensive manufacturing, does not require years of university education to acquire the requisite skills. A high-school graduate or less with some on the job training is often adequate for most of the jobs in manufacturing. Surplus labour from the informal sector, including agriculture, can move into labour-intensive manufacturing with minimum additional training, as long as they have basic skills like literacy and numeracy. This is what happened in Taiwan, South Korea, Thailand, Indonesia and China. Lately, even Vietnam and Bangladesh have followed course. Most importantly, as their industrial sector expanded, they absorbed more and more labour from agriculture – a sector with markedly lower productivity. Poverty declined as labour moved to a more productive sector, and the productivity of the remaining agricultural labour also increased. The growth was fast and also inclusive. It is important to mention that their respective governments actively aided this effort to develop a manufacturing sector in select areas with an eye on export markets. This was done through an industrial policy that included low interest loans, land grants, tax holidays and requisite infrastructure like power, container ports and other transportation networks. Albeit, it is easier to do it in countries where the democratic norms are rather flexible. 3. Why has India Failed to Follow the East Asian Script? Unlike the East and Southeast Asian governments, the Indian government did not direct the course of the post-1991 growth. Liberalisation certainly helped unleash market forces but the course of development was determined more or less through serendipity. When the licence raj ended in 1991, a few significant aspects of the reforms determined the subsequent course of the Indian growth story. In 1992, the government monopoly on the communication sector officially ended. The years between 1994 and 1999 saw a great deal of churning in this sector. Gradually, cell phones became pervasive. This was an opportune time for communication technology to take off in India. Due to excessive emphasis on public sector investments since 1960s in high-end technical and managerial institutions like the IITs and IIMs, there was a surplus of highly trained manpower available. At the same time, there was a sudden surge of demand all over the world for IT professionals as the Internet was appearing on the world stage. Indian engineers who were over-skilled for the Indian market had been migrating to the US since the 1960s where they had managed to establish quite a reputation. All this turned out to be fortuitous for Indian firms like TCS, WIPRO and Infosys to emerge on the world stage. Communications and business services grew to be India’s fastest growing sectors from 1993 to 2004 at 20.7% and 24.3% per annum, respectively. Software exports grew at the astronomical rate of 34% per annum over that period [LINKED_TEXT: 1] [URL: https://www.theindiaforum.in/article/what-should-we-do-about-indian-economy#tif-fn1] . [I]nclusive growth in India is a far more difficult prospect for India in 2020 than for China in 2000. India’s fast growth episode was propelled by exports of IT services. It was indeed an export-led growth. However, unlike China’s or South Korea’s growth through manufactured exports that absorbed low-skilled labour in vast numbers, India’s growth episode was led by a high-skilled service sector that failed to adequately absorb unskilled labour from agriculture. In the early 1990s, India could have also developed its manufacturing exports like China and South Korea. But there were several major obstacles: restrictive labour laws that created incentives for keeping the scale small; an outdated land acquisition law that made the process of acquiring land extremely messy; weak infrastructure limiting access to power, ports and roads and, most importantly, a badly educated labour force. Successive governments have found it challenging to address, let alone overcome, these obstacles. India has some unique problems that make any progress on this front difficult. First, any laws pertaining to agriculture and land are in the State List of the Constitution. This means that each state makes its own laws. The Centre can only override them if and only if they are repugnant to a law passed by Parliament. Land is also designated by whether it is agricultural land or not. In order to locate a large industrial project on any land designated as agricultural land, the state government needs to buy it from the farmers and sell it to the industrial house or change the land-use classification of the concerned area. In most states, this is a source of massive corruption and creates incentives for state politicians to block any attempt by the Centre to change these laws. Labour laws are in the Concurrent List of the Constitution. This means that the residual powers remain with the Centre, and the Central Government has greater degrees of freedom to change the laws. Yet, successive governments have found it politically difficult to do so. Rajasthan made some changes under the Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP) state government, but these changes were marginal. The existing laws are set up so as to put more restrictions on larger employers, especially with regard to adjusting the work force in response to changes in demand. This discourages attaining scales that would allow Indian manufacturers to compete internationally. These laws can be endured in situations where demand does not move cyclically, which was the case in India for many years in the past. However, international markets are notoriously cyclical, and firms need to adjust their output with a fair degree of flexibility. More importantly, since the mid-1990s, the Indian economy too has been displaying distinct business cycle behaviour, which makes the impact of these laws even more damaging. In fact, this could be an important factor driving the process of automation and robotics in Indian industry. After China entered the World Trade Organization (WTO) in 1999, it went on to occupy most of the unfilled space in the developed countries’ markets for manufactured goods. “Made in China” became a universal brand. It became much more difficult for countries like India to compete with China after that. In addition, the climate for international trade has recently changed. Developed countries have witnessed a denuding of their manufacturing sectors and the widespread resentment due to it has led to the election of right wing nationalists like Donald Trump. Countries such as the US are not so receptive any more to importing cheaper goods from low wage countries. Moreover, Indian workers now have to compete not just with Chinese and Vietnamese workers but also with robots and artificial intelligence. Even in India, firms have strong incentives to make production more capital-intensive. This is not just because of labour laws but also because long-term interest rates are not that much higher than short-term interest rates. The long and short of this is that inclusive growth in India is a far more difficult prospect for India in 2020 than for China in 2000. Yet, we must ask how other democratic nations like Thailand, Malaysia, and Indonesia have managed to solve these problems. Especially the problem of skilling the labour force. Even Bangladesh managed to develop a strong textile sector that could compete in international markets. When primary and secondary education itself fails to impart basic literacy and numeracy, any subsequent skilling programme is bound to fail. Why has public education been such a challenge for India? The genesis of India’s present problems of a lack of job creation and rural distress lies in these factors. Why did the growth of domestic investment and consequently the rate of gross capital formation slow down after 2008? It is important to note that the Asian success stories including that of China were based on an extremely high rate of investment. You need investment to create jobs and wages by bringing in new technology as well as by adding more capital (machines). India’s investment rate has not been bad at all, compared to the other Asian countries, except China. But it has faltered of late, particularly post the Global Financial Crisis of 2008. Why did the growth of domestic investment and consequently the rate of gross capital formation slow down after 2008?"},{"prompt":"What’s your best advice for a 17yearold turning 18?","completion":"17 years old, teenager., The desire to fly in the sky to feel free. New life new friends. Problem with parents, problem with teachers, who is the favorite person in this world? Who will be helpful to this teen? These are specific and difficult words. Parents watch them fashion, they watch them do their housework, they watch their hairstyles They see them as they are bunking classes, they see them lying and they hate their parents if they scold them. They only want to fulfill their wish Now I suggest parents to be polite to them. Treat them as a friend and talk to them. Appreciate them, scolding your child is not a solution. Take your kids on a picnic, to the movies Discuss any topic. Watch their activities. If they are doing some wrong activity, try to stop them immediately. tell them right and wrong If they are not good at education, don't scold them. try to give them the importance of education. See more: [LINKED_TEXT: 10 Pieces of Advice Every 17 Year Old Should Hear] [URL: https://fantasyfashioncare.com/things-a-17-year-old-should-know/]"},{"prompt":"w does one get officially married if they don’t believe in God? Would you still have to have a priest?","completion":"Marriage is a civil recognition of the relationship which results in legal obligations and entitlements. Even if you get married by a priest, you still must have a marriage license issue